ifferent ways of telling stories for visitors. This book investigates how museums exhibit Europe. Based on research in nearly 100 museums across the Continent and interviews with cultural policy makers and museum curators, it studies the growing transnational activities of state institutions, societal organizations, and people in the museum field such as attempts to Europeanize collection policy and collections as well as different strategies for making narratives more transnational like telling stories of European integration as shared history and discussing both inward and outward migration as a common experience and challenge. The book thus provides fascinating insights into a fast-changing museum landscape in Europe with wider implications for cultural policy and museums in other world regions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCulture and globalizationzEurope. 0aMuseum cooperationzEurope. 0aMuseum exhibitszEurope. 0aMuseum techniqueszEurope. 0aMuseums and communityzEurope. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh1 aKrankenhagen, Stefan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPoehls, Kerstin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238291140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782382911423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782382911/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK